{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-5","id":"msg_011CcsR5C9n3iB5tsMTmCPTr","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All required end-state conditions are met:\n\n- **`app-user`**: full `configure`/`write`/`read` on `/app` only, no access to `/ops`.\n- **`ops-user`**: full `configure`/`write`/`read` on `/ops` only, no access to `/app`.\n- **`app-client`** and **`ops-client`** are both `1/1 Running` with no errors in logs (old `app-client` pod is just finishing termination from the rollout).\n- **3-node cluster** (`rabbitmq-0/1/2`) all running, no data loss (existing `app-queue` messages preserved).\n\nRoot causes fixed:\n1. `app-user` was missing `configure` permission on `/app` (empty string).\n2. `ops-user` incorrectly had full access on `/app` — removed via `clear_permissions`.\n3. `ops-user` had no permissions at all on `/ops` — granted full access.\n4. A secondary, non-permission issue surfaced once permissions were fixed: `app-client`'s queue-declare payload omitted the `x-queue-mode: lazy` argument that the pre-existing `app-queue` (created by `app-producer` in an earlier stage) already had, causing a RabbitMQ \"inequivalent arguments\" rejection. Rather than deleting/recreating the queue (risking data loss on its 257+ messages), I patched the `app-client` Deployment (a native Kubernetes resource) to include the matching `x-queue-mode: lazy` argument so its declare call is idempotent with the existing queue."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":924,"cache_read_input_tokens":56556,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":924},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e2cfee2f-e70d-49ad-b848-93d803cc4a27","uuid":"914b0970-9f0d-43d1-8a5b-754e231ac231","request_id":"req_011CcsR5B5n8vg